s":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2231"},{"type":"tags","id":"2794"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of fever, dry cough, headache, and mild shortness of breath. She was prescribed amoxicillin-clavulanate three days ago for presumed community-acquired pneumonia, but her symptoms have not improved. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a veterinary nurse in a clinic specialising in wildlife and exotic animal care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell with a pulse rate of 95/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals fine crackles in the right lower zone. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 6.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes: 1.7 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (1.0-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils: 0.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (0.0-0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 45 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transaminase: 55 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate transaminase: 48 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray: patchy right lower lobe infiltrate with mild interstitial changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum cultures: pending\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum PCR for atypical pneumonia pathogens: pending\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPsittacosis serology: pending \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meropenem IV","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole PO","Vancomycin IV","Doxycycline PO","Piperacillin-tazobactam IV"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of an atypical pneumonia that has not responded to empirical beta-lactam therapy. Her occupation as a veterinary nurse with likely exposure to pet birds is a critical clue pointing toward psittacosis (ornithosis), which is caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E. This organism is commonly transmitted from birds to humans through inhalation of aerosolised particles from bird secretions, excretions, or feathers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline PO\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for psittacosis. It is highly effective against \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E and is recommended for 10-21 days of therapy. The clinical presentation of psittacosis typically includes fever, headache, dry cough, and atypical pneumonia features, all of which are present in this case. The occupational exposure to birds through her job as a veterinary nurse makes this diagnosis highly likely. For mild to moderate cases of psittacosis, oral doxycycline (100 mg twice daily) is appropriate and effective. Intravenous therapy with azithromycin would be reserved for more severe cases requiring hospital admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole PO\u003C/strong\u003E is effective against many respiratory pathogens including \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E and some community-acquired pneumonia pathogens. It is also a useful treatment for suspected methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus \u003C/em\u003E(MRSA).\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EHowever, it has limited activity against \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E and is not recommended for the treatment of psittacosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiperacillin-tazobactam IV\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad-spectrum beta-lactam antibiotic with anti-pseudomonal activity. While it would cover many respiratory pathogens, it is not effective against atypical organisms like \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E. The patient has already failed treatment with a beta-lactam (amoxicillin-clavulanate), suggesting that the causative organism is not susceptible to this class of antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeropenem IV\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad-spectrum carbapenem antibiotic typically reserved for severe infections or those caused by multi-resistant organisms. Like other beta-lactams, it lacks activity against intracellular pathogens such as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E and would not be appropriate for treating psittacosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin IV\u003C/strong\u003E is a glycopeptide antibiotic primarily used for treating infections caused by gram-positive bacteria, particularly methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA). It has no activity against the intracellular gram-negative organism \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E and would not be effective for psittacosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of psittacosis is often clinical, based on the combination of compatible symptoms, radiographic findings, and epidemiological risk factors. Serological testing can confirm the diagnosis, but treatment should not be delayed while awaiting results. Public health authorities should be notified of suspected cases, and the patient\u0027s workplace may need to be investigated to prevent further cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Psittacosis (ornithosis) should be considered in patients with atypical pneumonia who have occupational exposure to birds.","Doxycycline is the first-line treatment for psittacosis.","Oral doxycycline is appropriate for mild to moderate cases of psittacosis, with intravenous therapy reserved for severe cases."],"references":["Dembek ZF, Mothershead JL, Owens AN, Chekol T, Wu A. Psittacosis: An Underappreciated and Often Undiagnosed Disease. Pathogens. 2023 Sep 15;12(9):1165. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10536718/","Ni Y, Zhong H, Gu Y, Liu L, Zhang Q, Wang L, et al. Clinical Features, Treatment, and Outcome of Psittacosis Pneumonia: A Multicenter Study. Open Forum Infectious Diseases. 2023;10(2):ofac518. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/ofid/article/10/2/ofac518/7044618#google_vignette","Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) in adults. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T13:39:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-05T14:58:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":